<doc id="210091" wikidata="Q2032198" url="?curid=210091" title="Reflexive space">
<text>In the area of mathematics known as functional analysis, a reflexive space is a locally convex topological vector space for which the canonical evaluation map from formula_1 into its bidual (which is the strong dual of the strong dual of formula_1) is a homeomorphism (or equivalently, a TVS isomorphism). 
A normed space is reflexive if and only if this canonical evaluation map is surjective, in which case this (always linear) evaluation map is an isometric isomorphism and the normed space is a Banach space. Those spaces for which the canonical evaluation map is surjective are called semi-reflexive spaces. 

In 1951, R. C. James discovered a Banach space, now known as James&#x27; space, that is reflexive (meaning that the canonical evaluation map is not an isomorphism) but is nevertheless isometrically isomorphic to its bidual (any such isometric isomorphism is necessarily the canonical evaluation map). So importantly, for a Banach space to be reflexive, it is not enough for it to be isometrically isomorphic to its bidual; it is the canonical evaluation map in particular that has to be a homeomorphism.

Reflexive spaces play an important role in the general theory of locally convex TVSs and in the theory of Banach spaces in particular. Hilbert spaces are prominent examples of reflexive Banach spaces. Reflexive Banach spaces are often characterized by their geometric properties.

== Definition ==

;Definition of the bidual

Suppose that formula_1 is a topological vector space (TVS) over the field formula_4 (which is either the real or complex numbers) whose continuous dual space, formula_5 separates points on formula_1 (that is, for any formula_7 there exists some formula_8 such that formula_9). 
Let formula_10 (some texts write formula_11) denote the strong dual of formula_12 which is the vector space formula_13 of continuous linear functionals on formula_1 endowed with the topology of uniform convergence on bounded subsets of formula_1; 
this topology is also called the strong dual topology and it is the &quot;default&quot; topology placed on a continuous dual space (unless another topology is specified). 
If formula_1 is a normed space, then the strong dual of formula_1 is the continuous dual space formula_13 with its usual norm topology. 
The bidual of formula_12 denoted by formula_20 is the strong dual of formula_10; that is, it is the space formula_22 
If formula_1 is a normed space, then formula_24 is the continuous dual space of the Banach space formula_10 with its usual norm topology. 

;Definitions of the evaluation map and reflexive spaces

For any formula_26 let formula_27 be defined by formula_28 where formula_29 is a linear map called the evaluation map at formula_30; 
since formula_31 is necessarily continuous, it follows that formula_32 
Since formula_13 separates points on formula_12 the linear map formula_35 defined by formula_36 is injective where this map is called the evaluation map or the canonical map. 
Call formula_1 semi-reflexive if formula_35 is bijective (or equivalently, surjective) and we call formula_1 reflexive if in addition formula_40 is an isomorphism of TVSs.
A normable space is reflexive if and only if it is semi-reflexive or equivalently, if and only if the evaluation map is surjective.

