# All Hilbert spaces are reflexive, as are the Lp spaces formula_90 for formula_91 More generally: all uniformly convex Banach spaces are reflexive according to the Milman–Pettis theorem. The formula_92 and formula_93 spaces are not reflexive (unless they are finite dimensional, which happens for example when formula_94 is a measure on a finite set). Likewise, the Banach space formula_95 of continuous functions on formula_96 is not reflexive.
# The spaces formula_97 of operators in the Schatten class on a Hilbert space formula_98 are uniformly convex, hence reflexive, when formula_91 When the dimension of formula_98 is infinite, then formula_101 (the trace class) is not reflexive, because it contains a subspace isomorphic to formula_102 and formula_103 (the bounded linear operators on formula_98) is not reflexive, because it contains a subspace isomorphic to formula_105 In both cases, the subspace can be chosen to be the operators diagonal with respect to a given orthonormal basis of formula_106

=== Properties ===

Since every finite-dimensional normed space is a reflexive Banach space, only infinite-dimensional spaces can be non-reflexive.

If a Banach space formula_107 is isomorphic to a reflexive Banach space formula_1 then formula_107 is reflexive.

Every closed linear subspace of a reflexive space is reflexive. The continuous dual of a reflexive space is reflexive. Every quotient of a reflexive space by a closed subspace is reflexive.

Let formula_1 be a Banach space. The following are equivalent.
Since norm-closed convex subsets in a Banach space are weakly closed, 
it follows from the third property that closed bounded convex subsets of a reflexive space formula_1 are weakly compact. Thus, for every decreasing sequence of non-empty closed bounded convex subsets of formula_12 the intersection is non-empty. As a consequence, every continuous convex function formula_113 on a closed convex subset formula_114 of formula_12 such that the set
formula_116
is non-empty and bounded for some real number formula_117 attains its minimum value on formula_118

The promised geometric property of reflexive Banach spaces is the following: if formula_114 is a closed non-empty convex subset of the reflexive space formula_12 then for every formula_55 there exists a formula_122 such that formula_123 minimizes the distance between formula_30 and points of formula_118 This follows from the preceding result for convex functions, applied toformula_126 Note that while the minimal distance between formula_30 and formula_114 is uniquely defined by formula_129 the point formula_130 is not. The closest point formula_130 is unique when formula_1 is uniformly convex.

A reflexive Banach space is separable if and only if its continuous dual is separable. This follows from the fact that for every normed space formula_133 separability of the continuous dual formula_134 implies separability of formula_135

=== Super-reflexive space ===

Informally, a super-reflexive Banach space formula_1 has the following property: given an arbitrary Banach space formula_133 if all finite-dimensional subspaces of formula_107 have a very similar copy sitting somewhere in formula_12 then formula_107 must be reflexive. By this definition, the space formula_1 itself must be reflexive. As an elementary example, every Banach space formula_107 whose two dimensional subspaces are isometric to subspaces of formula_143 satisfies the parallelogram law, hence 
formula_107 is a Hilbert space, therefore formula_107 is reflexive. So formula_146 is super-reflexive.

The formal definition does not use isometries, but almost isometries. A Banach space formula_107 is finitely representable 
in a Banach space formula_1 if for every finite-dimensional subspace formula_149 of formula_107 and every formula_151 there is a subspace formula_152 of formula_1 such that the multiplicative Banach–Mazur distance between formula_152 and formula_149 satisfies
formula_156

A Banach space finitely representable in formula_146 is a Hilbert space. Every Banach space is finitely representable in formula_158 The Lp space formula_159 is finitely representable in formula_160

A Banach space formula_1 is super-reflexive if all Banach spaces formula_107 finitely representable in formula_1 are reflexive, or, in other words, if no non-reflexive space formula_107 is finitely representable in formula_51 The notion of ultraproduct of a family of Banach spaces 
allows for a concise definition: the Banach space formula_1 is super-reflexive when its ultrapowers are reflexive.

James proved that a space is super-reflexive if and only if its dual is super-reflexive.

=== Finite trees in Banach spaces ===

One of James&#x27; characterizations of super-reflexivity uses the growth of separated trees.
The description of a vectorial binary tree begins with a rooted binary tree labeled by vectors: a tree of height formula_167 in a Banach space formula_1 is a family of formula_169 vectors of formula_12 that can be organized in successive levels, starting with level 0 that consists of a single vector formula_171 the root of the tree, followed, for formula_172 by a family of formula_1732 vectors forming level formula_174
formula_175
that are the children of vertices of level formula_176 In addition to the tree structure, it is required here that each vector that is an internal vertex of the tree be the midpoint between its two children:
formula_177

Given a positive real number formula_117 the tree is said to be formula_179-separated if for every internal vertex, the two children are formula_179-separated in the given space norm:
formula_181

Theorem.
The Banach space formula_1 is super-reflexive if and only if for every formula_183 there is a number formula_184 such that every formula_179-separated tree contained in the unit ball of formula_1 has height less than formula_187

Uniformly convex spaces are super-reflexive.
Let formula_1 be uniformly convex, with modulus of convexity formula_189 and let formula_179 be a real number in formula_191 By the properties of the modulus of convexity, a formula_179-separated tree of height formula_193 contained in the unit ball, must have all points of level formula_194 contained in the ball of radius formula_195 By induction, it follows that all points of level formula_196 are contained in the ball of radius
formula_197

If the height formula_167 was so large that 
formula_199
then the two points formula_200 of the first level could not be formula_179-separated, contrary to the assumption. This gives the required bound formula_202 function of formula_203 only.

Using the tree-characterization, Enflo proved 
that super-reflexive Banach spaces admit an equivalent uniformly convex norm. Trees in a Banach space are a special instance of vector-valued martingales. Adding techniques from scalar martingale theory, Pisier improved Enflo&#x27;s result by showing that a super-reflexive space formula_1 admits an equivalent uniformly convex norm for which the modulus of convexity satisfies, for some constant formula_205 and some real number formula_206
formula_207

== Reflexive locally convex spaces ==

The notion of reflexive Banach space can be generalized to topological vector spaces in the following way.

Let formula_1 be a topological vector space over a number field formula_209 (of real numbers formula_210 or complex numbers formula_211). Consider its strong dual space formula_212 which consists of all continuous linear functionals formula_46 and is equipped with the strong topology formula_214 that is, the topology of uniform convergence on bounded subsets in formula_51 The space formula_10 is a topological vector space (to be more precise, a locally convex space), so one can consider its strong dual space formula_217 which is called the strong bidual space for formula_51 It consists of all continuous linear functionals formula_219 and is equipped with the strong topology formula_220 Each vector formula_55 generates a map formula_222 by the following formula:
formula_223
This is a continuous linear functional on formula_212 that is, formula_225 This induces a map called the evaluation map:
formula_226
This map is linear. If formula_1 is locally convex, from the Hahn–Banach theorem it follows that formula_62 is injective and open (that is, for each neighbourhood of zero formula_229 in formula_1 there is a neighbourhood of zero formula_231 in formula_232 such that formula_233). But it can be non-surjective and/or discontinuous.

A locally convex space formula_1 is called 
* semi-reflexive if the evaluation map formula_235 is surjective (hence bijective),
* reflexive if the evaluation map formula_235 is surjective and continuous (in this case formula_62 is an isomorphism of topological vector spaces).



=== Semireflexive spaces ===
==== Characterizations ====

If formula_1 is a Hausdorff locally convex space then the following are equivalent:
#formula_1 is semireflexive;
#The weak topology on formula_1 had the Heine-Borel property (that is, for the weak topology formula_241 every closed and bounded subset of formula_242 is weakly compact). 
#If linear form on formula_13 that continuous when formula_13 has the strong dual topology, then it is continuous when formula_13 has the weak topology; 
#formula_246 is barreled; 
#formula_1 with the weak topology formula_248 is quasi-complete.

=== Characterizations of reflexive spaces ===

If formula_1 is a Hausdorff locally convex space then the following are equivalent:
#formula_1 is reflexive;
#formula_1 is semireflexive and infrabarreled;
#formula_1 is semireflexive and barreled;
#formula_1 is barreled and the weak topology on formula_1 had the Heine-Borel property (that is, for the weak topology formula_255 every closed and bounded subset of formula_242 is weakly compact).
#formula_1 is semireflexive and quasibarrelled.

If formula_1 is a normed space then the following are equivalent:
#formula_1 is reflexive;
#The closed unit ball is compact when formula_1 has the weak topology formula_261
#formula_1 is a Banach space and formula_10 is reflexive.
#Every sequence formula_264 with formula_265 for all formula_167 of nonempty closed bounded convex subsets of formula_1 has nonempty intersection.

=== Sufficient conditions ===

;Normed spaces

A normed space that is semireflexive is a reflexive Banach space.
A closed vector subspace of a reflexive Banach space is reflexive.

Let formula_1 be a Banach space and formula_269 a closed vector subspace of formula_51 If two of formula_271 and formula_272 are reflexive then they all are. This is why reflexivity is referred to as a .

;Topological vector spaces

If a barreled locally convex Hausdorff space is semireflexive then it is reflexive.

The strong dual of a reflexive space is reflexive.Every Montel space is reflexive. And the strong dual of a Montel space is a Montel space (and thus is reflexive).

